label chapter5:

    # [Scene: Floating Farm & Coral Nursery | Morning — rising tide]

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid minimal strings enter, building a quiet, urgent pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water lapping; gulls muffled by wind; a distant metallic ping — sensor heartbeat]
    "You already said yes. The words you gave in the Community Hall still sit warm and sharp in your chest: you'll lead the marsh pilot. Now the pilot is a chorus of hands and tools and breath, and you are the center conductor whether you meant to be or not."
    "Salt and damp press into your nostrils. Your sleeves are damp at the cuff. You can feel the satchel at your hip, notebooks tucked inside like promises. Around you, seed trays tilt at angles, new cordgrass"
    "shoots reaching, the plastic frames of coral nurseries flashing aquamarine when the sun finds them through cloud. Small green indicator LEDs wink on the sensor arrays: heartbeats of the thing you're trying not to let fail."
    show kaito_sakamura at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kaito_sakamura "Height at the outer ridge is reading low — we need to add another rib. If the tide runs higher than forecast it eats this whole bed."
    show maya_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_chen "We have extra bamboo, but the anchoring lines are frayed. (pointing) That splice needs a double lash."
    "You move without thinking: reach, test, tie a knot the way your grandmother showed you on a shorter dock when you were a child. Muscle memory fills in the gaps your nerves leave. Your hands know"
    "this work as well as any code. They know the way a plant settles into packing soil, the way a rope replies."
    show marin_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marin_alvarez "I'll patch the splice, Kaito. Maya, get that sensor array up and put the north anchor on a double-redundant line."
    "Kaito looks up, that small softening at his eyes that is more mercy than praise. He walks over, shoulders angled as if to shelter the work itself."

    kaito_sakamura "You sure you're not trying to do everything at once?"
    "You look at the notebook in your palm — diagrams, community sign-off notes, a smudged apology written in the margins. You are sure; this is the shape of atonement you can hand someone."

    marin_alvarez "I'm sure."
    hide kaito_sakamura
    hide maya_chen
    hide marin_alvarez

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Quiet alert chirp; wind picks up]
    "Rin arrives, breathless, a stack of wet posters tucked under her arm. Her freckled face is bright with the small, flinty hope she keeps in her pockets."
    show rin_okubo at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rin_okubo "Luka's here with the old maps. He says the groups that built these banks—his grandfather's crew—used ceremonies before they started. Wants to run a blessing before we anchor the outer frame."
    "Luka Sorensen steps onto the platform, every inch of him a weathered story. He plants his cane, leans in with the gravity of decades."
    show luka_sorensen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_sorensen "Saltline forgets the language of the marsh and the marsh forgets us. You bind them together like a marriage. Make it a marriage with witnesses."
    "His eyes find yours and something like a small, necessary pressure presses on the back of your throat. The project feels less like engineering and more like a vow."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell — an urgent, rising motif. The wind crescendos]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low, resounding thump — a data packet landing; the portable rig hums]
    "Ishaan arrives with Elena at his side. Their steps are professional, precise; air that smells faintly of citrus and new equipment. Elena's trench coat flaps; a projected overlay flickers near her wrist. She carries the kind of calm that remembers cities before storms."
    show elena_moro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_moro "Morning. The agency's modelers ran a conditional simulation overnight. We can move funds this quarter to install engineered ribs along the outer perimeter — composite pylons that tie into your revetment. They reduce overtopping risk by thirty-seven percent in our projections."
    hide rin_okubo
    show ishaan_rao at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ishaan_rao "There are contractual frameworks attached. We need oversight on the engineered components. Data-sharing. A clause for emergency adaptive control — agency teams can intervene if model thresholds hit."
    "The words land like stones dropped in a pond. The ripples widen across faces. Some of those ripples flatten into practical calculation; others curl with a colder edge."
    "Kaito's jaw tightens. The wooden peg in his hand is suddenly very important to him."
    hide luka_sorensen
    show kaito_sakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kaito_sakamura "So you pay for half of our costs and you get veto power over what the marsh can be?"

    elena_moro "Not veto power. Technical oversight, to ensure the engineered elements meet regional standards. We can protect more people that way. This is pragmatism."
    "You can hear the tenderness in Kaito's voice war with the pragmatic logic in Elena's. You are standing between two kinds of certainty."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Pulse accelerates; percussion like coming rain]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A higher-volume alert — the rig beeps faster; a model line spikes again]
    "Maya, hands still wet with nursery water, steps forward hard enough that droplets fly."
    hide elena_moro
    show maya_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_chen "We can't hand the shoreline off to an algorithm. The marsh isn't a box to be engineered out of culture. Remember the displacement from the old retrofit? We almost lost the eelgrass terraces."
    "Ishaan folds his hands, patient, practiced."

    ishaan_rao "And without backing, the pilot stalls. Money means materials, monitoring. What do you propose? Pure community labor to face rising seas? That is noble, but politic—"
    "Rin cuts him off, voice higher than usual."
    hide ishaan_rao
    show rin_okubo at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rin_okubo "Politics doesn't plant roots."
    "Luka exhales, every breath a slow rope of salt and memory."
    hide kaito_sakamura
    show luka_sorensen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_sorensen "Both are true. We either use what is offered and accept constraints, or we keep control and risk being under-resourced when the tide comes harder."
    "The rig pulses again; the display shows a conditional line: modeled storm surge that could test your outer rib within weeks, not months. The urgency is no longer abstract."
    "Your chest tightens. The people you love are looking to you to translate this tangle into action that doesn't fracture what Saltline is."
    "You feel the old guilt — the project long ago that displaced a marsh you once defended with slides and grant promises. It taught you how brittle good intentions can be. You don't want to repeat that calculus with other people's homes and histories."
    hide maya_chen
    show marin_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marin_alvarez "If we take money, what exactly are the 'oversight' terms?"
    "Elena Moro's smile is a practice of diplomacy."
    hide rin_okubo
    show elena_moro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_moro "We require sensor telemetry access for the engineered pylons, a clause to schedule agency inspections, and the right to deploy automated actuators if certain thresholds are exceeded. We also commit to training local teams and co-branding the installation."
    "Kaito steps in, voice roughening."
    hide luka_sorensen
    show kaito_sakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kaito_sakamura "Co-branding? That sounds like a sign on a seawall. It sounds like a partition between our gatherings and the land."

    "Elena Moro (soft)" "We protect more people faster that way. Your marsh works as protection and habitat, but our models show it needs a hard backbone to survive severe anomalies."

    "Maya (angry, pleading)" "And whose anomalies decide what a marsh is? Your models replace stories with numbers."

    "Ishaan (even)" "We need to be realistic. You know that. Funding is a lever. If you refuse, you get autonomy and uncertainty."

    "Rin (murmuring)" "If we accept, will they let Mama Sorensen keep her altar on the north bank? Will Luka's ceremony still belong to us?"
    "Elena hesitates — or calculates the public relations benefit of empathy."

    elena_moro "Cultural elements can be preserved if they don't compromise structural integrity. We can write protections into the contract for specific sites."
    "Kaito's face hardens. His hand finds yours for half a second, a quick, human anchor."

    kaito_sakamura "Whatever you decide, I need to know you looked for the small ways, too. Not only the big numbers."

    marin_alvarez "I know."

    menu:
        "Check the integrity of the north anchor now":
            "You step to the rail, fingers probing the splice. The line is rough but holds—enough for today. Relief warms your shoulders for a second."
        "Ask Luka about the ceremony details before deciding":
            "You kneel beside Luka as he traces the map with a stick. He names the old vows and the places they mattered; your decision feels heavier with that language added."

    menu:
        "Double down on community-led hybrid designs and refuse conditional agency panels.":
            jump chapter7
        "Accept conditional agency support for a targeted retrofit while protecting key marsh plots.":
            jump chapter9
        "Propose a federated governance pilot—shared oversight between the agency and community council.":
            jump chapter15
    return
